Valid Parentheses (LeetCode 20)
Min Stack (LeetCode 155)
Implement Stack Using Queues (LeetCode 225)
Implement Queue Using Stacks (LeetCode 232)
Remove Outermost Parentheses (LeetCode 1021)


These drill the fundamentals. If these feel hard, your stack basics aren’t stable.

Level 2 — Monotonic Stack (the real stack problems)
This is where developers fall apart if they don’t know patterns.
You either master these or you’ll keep getting trapped later.

Next Greater Element I (LeetCode 496)
Next Greater Element II (LeetCode 503)
Daily Temperatures (LeetCode 739)
Stock Span Problem (classic)
Next Smaller Element (GFG)

These teach you the real point of stacks:
processing sequences while maintaining a decreasing/increasing order.

Level 3 — Hard but extremely common interview patterns
If you reach here, your stack game is clean.
Largest Rectangle in Histogram (LeetCode 84)
Maximal Rectangle (LeetCode 85)
Trapping Rain Water (LeetCode 42) – stack version
132 Pattern (LeetCode 456)
Score of Parentheses (LeetCode 856)

These problems appear in FAANG-level interviews.
If you can explain them clearly, you’re no longer a beginner.

Level 4 — Real skill check (only if you want domination)
Not required but excellent for mastery.
Nearest Greater to Left/Right (GFG)
Evaluate Reverse Polish Notation (LeetCode 150)
Basic Calculator II (LeetCode 227)
Decode String (LeetCode 394)
Simplify Path (LeetCode 71)